<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910619-0058</DOCNO><DOCID>910619-0058.</DOCID><HL>   SEC Alleges Officials   Of CapitalBanc Made   Fraudulent Loans</HL><DATE>06/19/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C13</SO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)SECURITIES REGULATIONS AND ENFORCEMENT (RGU)</IN><NS>SECURITIES REGULATION (RGU)</NS><GV>SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)</GV><RE>DELAWARE (DE)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The Securities and Exchange Commissioncharged the current chairman and a former chairman ofCapitalBanc Corp. and four others with participating in aseries of fraudulent loan schemes, including one designed tohide the misappropriation of $2.7 million.   In a civil suit filed in federal court here, the SECcharged that the loan schemes and a sham transaction causedCapitalBanc to misstate its income for several periods. TheDelaware bank-holding company's primary subsidiary, CapitalNational Bank, was declared insolvent last July.</LP><TEXT>   The suit names Carlos Cordova, CapitalBanc's formerchairman; Renan A. Mazorra, chairman and president ofCapitalBanc; Renan R. Mazorra, a member of the company'sadvisory board and Renan A. Mazorra's father; Nasrallah Misk,a former customer of Capital National; Ramon Martinez III,former vice president of Capital National; and Luis Alfaro, adirector of CapitalBanc.   Without admitting or denying allegations, both Mazorras,Messrs. Misk, Martinez and Alfaro agreed to a settlement thatenjoins them from further violations of securities laws. TheSEC said action against Mr. Cordova and CapitalBanc ispending and that its investigation of the case is continuing.   The suit alleges that Mr. Cordova misappropriated $2.7million from Capital National in 1987 to repay loans that heand the elder Mazorra used to buy stock in the company. TheSEC also charged that Mr. Misk borrowed at least $10 millionfrom Capital National in the names of at least 10 nomineeborrowers in order to evade legal limits on bank lending to asingle individual. Mr. Martinez assisted in awarding theloans, and some were approved by Mr. Cordova, who received$1.75 million on proceeds from the loans, the SEC said.   After Mr. Mazorra succeeded Mr. Cordova as president ofCapitalBanc, Capital National continued to make nomineeloans, including two in which Mr. Alfaro was the nominee, theSEC said. The SEC charged that the lending and relatedactivities affected CapitalBanc's filings with the SEC for1987 and 1988.   Lawyers for Messrs. Alvaro, Martinez, Misk and Cordovacouldn't be reached for comment. The two Mazorras alsocouldn't be reached.</TEXT></DOC>